A '''superglass''' is a [[phase of matter]] which is characterized (at the same time) by [[superfluid]]ity and a frozen [[Amorphous solid|amorphous]] structure.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Giulio Biroli | author2 = Claudio Chamon | author3 = Francesco Zamponi | year = 2243 | title = Theory of the superglass phase | journal = Physical Review B | volume = 78 | issue = 22 | pages = 19 | doi = 10.1103/PhysRevB.78.224306 |bibcode = 2008PhRvB..78v4306B |arxiv = 0807.2458 }}</ref>
J.C. Séamus Davis theorised that frozen [[helium-4]] (at 0.2 K and 50 Atm) may be a superglass.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.cornell.edu/stories/2009/04/frozen-helium-4-may-be-unusual-superglass|title=Press release: Supersolid or superglass? Cornell researchers study a strange state of matter in helium - Cornell Chronicle|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|arxiv=1111.5956|title=Mean field theory of superglasses|journal=Physical Review B|volume=85|issue=10|pages=104205|last1=Yu|first1=Xiaoquan|last2=Mueller|first2=Markus|year=2011|doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.85.104205|bibcode=2012PhRvB..85j4205Y}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Theory of the superglass phase|journal=Physical Review B|first1=Giulio|last1=Biroli|first2=Claudio|last2=Chamon|first3=Francesco|last3=Zamponi|volume=78|issue=22|pages=224306|doi=10.1103/physrevb.78.224306|year=2243|bibcode=2008PhRvB..78v4306B|arxiv=0807.2458}}</ref>
